# root crontab on kodiak — system-level scheduled work.
#
# Two categories of entries:
#   1. iDrive's auto-installed entries (idrive's .deb adds these on install
#      to keep idrivecron.service alive — auto-restart if it dies). Leaving
#      them alone; if a future re-run of bin/install-idrive-on-kodiak.sh
#      reinstalls iDrive, these will be re-added by their installer.
#   2. ADR-005 snapshot-clone refresh — daily at 02:30, between A1's 02:00
#      replication landing fresh snapshots and idrivecron's 03:30 backup
#      kicking off. Without this, iDrive would keep backing up the same
#      day-frozen clones forever, ignoring new saratoga data.
#
# Install:
#   sudo crontab -u root configs/cron/root-crontab
#
# Notes:
#   - No MAILTO set — root on kodiak has no msmtprc, so cron mail wouldn't
#     deliver anyway. The refresh-clones script is silent on success;
#     downstream coverage is iDrive's own per-run report email (which catches
#     any case where iDrive's scan fails because clones aren't in place).
#   - If we ever want immediate failure visibility, options:
#       a) drop /root/.msmtprc (mirroring ~ldavis/.msmtprc) and wrap entries
#          via bin/mail-on-output.sh;
#       b) add a NOPASSWD sudoers entry for ldavis on idrive-refresh-clones.sh
#          and move the entry to ldavis's crontab (uses existing msmtp setup).

# iDrive scheduler keep-alive (installed by the iDrive .deb postinst)
@reboot sleep 10; systemctl start idrivecron
*/10 * * * * systemctl start idrivecron

# ADR-005 — refresh ZFS clones from latest saratoga snapshots before
# idrivecron's daily backup fires (03:30). 02:30 gives 30-minute headroom
# after A1 replication completes at 02:00.
30 2 * * * /home/ldavis/development/server-backups/bin/idrive-refresh-clones.sh
